'''Shaina Horenstein''' was the youngest daughter of Rabbi [[Yosef Yitzchak Schneersohn]], the sixth [[Rebbe]] of the [[Chabad]] [[Hasidic]] movement. In the Chabad community, she is referred to as '''Rebbitzin Shaina'''.<ref>[http://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/1902777/jewish/Today-is-the-Day.htm ''Today is the Day'']. Kehot Publication Society. Chabad.org. Accessed April 24, 2014.</ref>

==Biography==
Sheina Horenstein was born Sheina Schnnersohn, the youngest daughter of Rabbi [[Yosef Yitzchak Schneersohn]], the sixth [[Rebbe]] of the [[Chabad]], and [[Nechama Dinah Schneersohn]]. As with many members of the Schneersohn dynasty, Sheina is referred to as "Rebbitzin Sheina" by many Chabad Hasidim.

Rebbitzin Sheina married Menachem Mendel Horenstein on Tuesday, June 14, 1932 (Hebrew: Sivan 10, 5692).<ref>Schneerson, Menachem Mendel. [http://www.sichosinenglish.org/books/eternal-joy-2/12.htm ''Eternal Joy''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425031807/http://www.sichosinenglish.org/books/eternal-joy-2/12.htm |date=2014-04-25 }}. Vaad Lehafotzas Sichos. SichosInEnglish.org. Accessed April 24, 2014.</ref> Her wedding was attended by many notable rabbis and Hasidic Rebbes.<ref>Raynitz, Avrohom. [http://www.beismoshiach.org/_pdf/435.pdf  "Rabbi Schneur Zalman Gurary."] ''Beish Moshiach Magazine''. Cheshvan 5764 (2004). Accessed April 24, 2014.</ref> The couple lived near Rabbi Yosef Yitzchak in Poland for a number of years and were permanent members of his court.

Sheina and her husband were killed by the Nazis during [[World War II]] in [[Treblinka]].<ref>Lightstone, Mordechai. [http://www.lubavitch.com/news/article/2028212/Transition-in-Lubavitch-January-28-1950.html Transition in Lubavitch]. ''Lubavitch.com''. January 25, 2010. Accessed April 24, 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.sichosinenglish.org/books/letters-rebbe-3/104.htm ''Igros Kodesh''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425003848/http://www.sichosinenglish.org/books/letters-rebbe-3/104.htm |date=2014-04-25 }}. Sichos in English. Accessed April 24, 2014.</ref> The [[yartzeit]], or anniversary of their death, is marked each year on the 25th of the Hebrew month of [[Cheshvan]].<ref>[http://www.lchaimweekly.org/cgi-bin/lessons.cgi?date=31101964 "Hayom Yom"]. ''L'Chaim Weekly''. Accessed April 24, 2014.</ref>

==Memorial==
[[File:Chaya Mushka Schneerson grave.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Tomb of Sheina's sister, Rebbitzin Chaya Mushka Schneerson]]
The tomb of Sheina's older sister, [[Chaya Mushka Schneerson]], contains a dedication to her death during the [[holocaust]]. The tomb is visited regularly by Chabad Hasidim.<ref>[http://www.shturem.org/index.php?section=artdays&id=1912 Rebbitzin Chaya Mushka Schneerson]. ''Shturem''. Accessed April 24, 2014.</ref>

